LEAD = """<strong>Chain of custody in precious metals is the unbroken, documented record of who held the metal at every stage of its journey &mdash; from mine production, through aggregation, transport and export, to receipt at the refinery</strong> &mdash; evidenced by sealed packaging, transfer records, weights and signatures at each handover. It serves three masters at once: physical security (nothing was substituted or removed), settlement integrity (the lot assayed is the lot shipped), and compliance (the metal's origin claims are provable)."""

BODY = """
<h2>What a Chain of Custody Record Contains</h2>
<p>For each link in the chain &mdash; every change of hands or location &mdash; the record shows:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Who</strong> &mdash; the identified party releasing and the party receiving, with signatures;</li>
<li><strong>What</strong> &mdash; description of the material, piece count, and seal numbers;</li>
<li><strong>How much</strong> &mdash; weight at handover, on identified scales;</li>
<li><strong>When and where</strong> &mdash; date, time and location of the transfer;</li>
<li><strong>Integrity evidence</strong> &mdash; tamper-evident seals checked intact on receipt, with any discrepancy documented immediately.</li>
</ul>
<p>The test of the chain is continuity: the receiving record of each link matches the releasing record of the one before, from the first smelt at the mine to the receiving floor of the refinery.</p>

<h2>The Typical Chain for a Dor&eacute; Shipment</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Mine</strong> &mdash; production recorded; dor&eacute; bars numbered, weighed and sealed.</li>
<li><strong>Internal transport</strong> &mdash; armoured carrier signs for sealed boxes; weights confirmed.</li>
<li><strong>Exporter's vault</strong> &mdash; receipt against seals; lot assembled for export; pre-export assay sampling documented.</li>
<li><strong>Customs</strong> &mdash; physical verification against the <a href="/knowledge/gold-export-procedures-explained/">export documents</a>; customs seals applied.</li>
<li><strong>Secure air freight</strong> &mdash; valuables carrier uplift under airway bill; insured per <a href="/knowledge/what-is-a-cif-gold-transaction/">CIF terms</a>.</li>
<li><strong>Destination clearance</strong> &mdash; import verification; carrier delivers to refinery.</li>
<li><strong>Refinery receiving</strong> &mdash; seals checked, lot weighed, receipt issued &mdash; the chain's final link, and the start of the <a href="/knowledge/how-does-a-gold-refinery-assay-work/">assay process</a>.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Why Chains of Custody Decide Deals</h2>
<p><strong>Security:</strong> gold is uniquely substitutable &mdash; a sealed, weighed, witnessed chain is the only assurance that the metal assayed in Dubai is the metal that left the mine.</p>
<p><strong>Settlement:</strong> weight discrepancies between links are found and attributed immediately, instead of surfacing as an unexplained shortfall at final assay &mdash; where they become the seller's loss.</p>
<p><strong>Compliance:</strong> origin claims are only as good as the custody record behind them. Refineries discharging <a href="/knowledge/oecd-gold-supply-chain-guidance/">OECD-aligned due diligence</a> treat custody gaps as origin uncertainty &mdash; and origin uncertainty, under <a href="/knowledge/sanctions-compliance-for-precious-metals/">sanctions regimes with origin-based gold bans</a>, is legal risk no compliant buyer will accept.</p>
<p><strong>Insurance:</strong> transit cover depends on approved carriers and procedures; a custody gap can void the very insurance the shipment relies on.</p>

<h2>Example</h2>
<p>A 25 kg lot shows a 60-gram discrepancy between the exporter's vault record and refinery receiving weight. Because every link is documented, the difference is traced in hours: the vault scale's calibration certificate had lapsed, and the corrected figures reconcile. Without the chain, the same 60 grams would be an unattributable dispute between seller and refinery at settlement &mdash; with the seller, as the party claiming the higher weight, bearing the burden of proof it could not meet.</p>

<h2>Building a Strong Chain Cheaply</h2>
<p>Chain of custody is procedure, not technology: numbered tamper-evident seals, calibrated and certificated scales, standard transfer forms signed at every handover, photographs at sealing and receipt, and immediate documentation of any anomaly. Digital traceability systems increasingly supplement this in formal supply chains, but the disciplined paper-and-seal chain remains the accepted standard &mdash; and the absence of one is, for refineries and banks alike, a reason to walk away.</p>
"""

